      <h2>Smith Lake Full Pool Elevation</h2>
      <p>Lewis Smith Lake's full pool elevation — the target water level that Alabama Power tries to maintain during summer — is <strong>510 feet above mean sea level</strong>. At full pool, the lake covers approximately 21,000 surface acres with 642 miles of shoreline. The maximum depth reaches 264 feet near the dam.</p>

      <p>Water elevation is measured continuously by Alabama Power and reported through their shoreline management system. The current level is directly relevant to fishing, navigation, dock access, and shoreline conditions.</p>

      <h2>How Water Levels Affect Fishing</h2>

      <h3>High Water (At or Above Full Pool)</h3>
      <p>When Smith Lake is at or above full pool, fish — especially bass — spread out into the flooded vegetation and timber that only gets inundated at high levels. This can be both a blessing and a challenge: the fish may be shallower and more active, but they have more places to hide. Work the flooded brush and timber edges with swimbaits, spinnerbaits, and shallow crankbaits. Crappie fishing around docks and timber is particularly good during high water periods.</p>

      <h3>Normal Pool (510 ft ±2 feet)</h3>
      <p>This is Smith Lake's "home base" condition and when most anglers see the lake. Structure is predictable, fish relate to normal points and ledges, and dock access is standard. Most of the fishing information on this site assumes near-normal pool conditions.</p>

      <h3>Low Water / Drawdown (Below 506 ft)</h3>
      <p>When Alabama Power draws down the lake — which happens most significantly in fall and winter — fish concentrate near remaining water. A drawdown moves fish off the banks and compresses them onto main lake structure and channel edges. This can actually create excellent fishing: there's less water to cover, and the fish are more predictable. However, low water exposes rocks, stumps, and shallow bars that can damage hulls and props at normal pool. Know the lake's hazards and run slower in unfamiliar areas during a drawdown.</p>

      <p>Typically, the winter drawdown at Smith Lake begins in late October or November and reaches its lowest point in January or February before the lake is refilled for the spring and summer recreation season.</p>

